[2] Michigan: HAV Emergency Plan
Date: Tue 31 Oct 2017 2:10 PM
Source: WCPO, WXYZ [edited]
http://www.wcpo.com/news/national/hepatitis-a-outbreak-leads-michigan-to-launch-emergency-plan


The Michigan Department of Health and Human Services [MDHHS] is activating an emergency plan in response an outbreak of hepatitis A. The number of cases continues to rise in Michigan. The department is activating what is called the Community Health Emergency Coordination Center.

"To help coordinate Michigan's response to the hepatitis A outbreak, we are opening the Community Health Emergency Coordination Center to assist the multiple local public health jurisdictions involved in the response and prevention of further cases," said MDHHS Director Nick Lyon.

The emergency coordination center will provide support to health departments, hospitals, EMS and other health care providers. Health care providers are asked to encourage hepatitis A vaccination.

"We know that the hepatitis A vaccine is more than 90 percent effective in protecting someone who may be exposed to hepatitis A," said Dr Eden Wells, Chief Medical Executive with the MDHHS. "Without a single source associated with these cases, the importance of vaccination and proper hygiene is vital to ensuring we stop the person-to-person spread of hepatitis A."

There have been 457 confirmed cases of hepatitis A since 1 Aug 2016. This number includes 18 fatalities associated with the outbreak and affected a number of cities; City of Detroit, Huron, Ingham, Lapeer, Livingston, Macomb, Monroe, Oakland, Sanilac, St Clair, Washtenaw, and Wayne Counties reported to MDHHS.

To reduce the risk of contracting hepatitis A, health officials recommend the following points of emphasis:
- Wash hands frequently, especially after using the bathroom, changing diapers, and before preparing and eating food.
- Clean and disinfect all surface areas if someone in the household or workplace has symptoms., especially areas such as toilets. sinks, trashcans, doorknobs and faucet handles.
- Do not prepare food if you have symptoms and refrain from food preparation for at least 3 days after symptoms have ended, or two weeks after onset of clinical symptoms, whichever is longer.
- Get the Hepatitis A vaccine.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[With more than 450 cases and 18 deaths over more than a year and no sign of lessening of the outbreak in southeastern Michigan, such an emergency declaration seems overdue. Approaching the outbreak, as San Diego county has done, by adapting the prevention paradigm to address sanitation and strongly recommending immunization of food handlers may have an effect, but it is not clear that those modalities are to be considered. Again, unlike San Diego, the outbreak here, which was more prevalent in drug abusers, seems now to have had increased spillover into the MSM population. It is not clear that the issues with lead in Flint's water and the cluster of legionellosis possibly linked to contaminated water (Legionellosis - USA (02): (MI) genotyping, RFI Archive Number: 20170217.4846471), which has now resulted in legal action against some officials, may have diverted attention from the HAV outbreak. - Mod.LL]


