[3] Michigan (Detroit): food handlers cases
Date: Mon 30 Oct 2017 5:25 PM EDT
Source: MLive [edited]
http://www.mlive.com/news/detroit/index.ssf/2017/10/new_hepatitis_cases_verified_i.html


Two cases of hepatitis A have been verified in connection with Detroit [food] service employees at a Little Caesars Pizza store and Firewater Bar and Grill, according to Detroit health officials. "The Detroit Health Department is conducting a thorough investigation of both establishments to ensure appropriate food handing and cleaning protocols are being followed," says a statement issued [Mon 30 Oct 2017]. "The Detroit Health Department has notified both establishments that infected employees are not to return to work until approved by their doctor."

The Little Caesars is located at 12712 Fenkell, and Firewater Bar and Grill at 6521 John R. "Those who patronized Firewater Bar and Grill from 15 Oct 2017 through 24 Oct 2017, or consumed food from Little Caesars Pizza at 12712 Fenkell in Detroit from 15 Oct 2017 through 26 Oct 2017 should consult their primary care provider to receive the hepatitis A vaccine as early as possible, and before 7 Nov 2017," Detroit health officials said.

The city is offering free hepatitis A vaccinations this week, on [Tue 31 Oct, Thu 2 Nov, and Fri 3 Nov 2017], from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. and [Wed 1 Nov 20178], from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. at the Samaritan Center, 5555 Conner in Detroit; and the Family Place, 8726 Woodward in Detroit.

The number of hepatitis A cases in Southeast Michigan has continued to rise as the Michigan Department of Health and Human Services investigates possible sources of the outbreak.

Detroit health officials say there is a "low" risk of transmission by a food handler.

[Byline: Gus Burns]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In the past, unless there have been secondary cases of hepatitis A related to the infected food handler, I have avoided posting such cases but, especially in outbreak settings such as San Diego and southeast Michigan, the infected food handler may become a significant factor in feeding the outbreaks. The cases reported relate to overt clinical cases usually with jaundice in the food handler but even in adults, many cases of acute HAV infection are totally subclinical (no symptoms at all) or anicteric (nonspecific symptoms without jaundice) and these episodes are not found. Healthcare workers are required to be immunized against a variety of infections in part to protect the patients. Consideration of requiring HAV immunization in all food handlers has occurred in the past, perhaps now would be the time to reconsider. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Michigan can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5417867,225]
